<subSubSection lastPageId="6" lastPageNumber="459" pageId="5" pageNumber="458" type="remarks">
<paragraph pageId="5" pageNumber="458">Remarks.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="5" pageNumber="458">
The names 
<taxonomicName genus="H." lsidName="H. bouvieri" pageId="5" pageNumber="458" rank="species" species="bouvieri">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="458">H. bouvieri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName genus="H." lsidName="H. bonnanius" pageId="5" pageNumber="458" rank="species" species="bonnanius">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="458">H. bonnanius</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
were synonymized with 
<taxonomicName genus="H." lsidName="H. ramagei" pageId="5" pageNumber="458" rank="species" species="ramagei">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="458">H. ramagei</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by 
<bibRefCitation author="Pilsbry, HA" journalOrPublisher="Academy of Natural Sciences of Philadelphia, Philadelphia" pageId="8" pageNumber="461" refId="B29" refString="Pilsbry, HA, 1901. Manual of conchology, second series. Pulmonata. Vol. 14. Oriental bulimoid Helicidae; Odontostomidae; Cerionidae. Academy of Natural Sciences of Philadelphia, Philadelphia" title="Manual of conchology, second series. Pulmonata. Vol. 14. Oriental bulimoid Helicidae; Odontostomidae; Cerionidae." year="1901">Pilsbry (1901)</bibRefCitation>
; this decision is followed here. The syntype of 
<taxonomicName genus="H." lsidName="H. bouvieri" pageId="5" pageNumber="458" rank="species" species="bouvieri">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="458">H. bouvieri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 4" captionStartId="F4" captionText="Figure 4. Hyperaulax ramagei. A-C. Syntype of Bonnanius bouvieri, MNHN-IM- 2000 - 28020 (MNHN). D. Reproduction of &quot; Turbine  44 &quot; of Buonanni (1861), the holotype of Bonnanius bonnanius. E. Protoconch detail, NHMUK 1902.10.16.4." figureDoi="10.3897/zse.95.38259.figure4" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/339177" pageId="5" pageNumber="458" tableDoi="10.3897/zse.95.38259.figure4">
Fig. 4
<normalizedToken originalValue="A–C">A-C</normalizedToken>
</figureCitation>
) is indistinguishable from 
<taxonomicName genus="H." lsidName="H. ramagei" pageId="5" pageNumber="458" rank="species" species="ramagei">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="458">H. ramagei</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but the discussion regarding 
<taxonomicName genus="H." lsidName="H. bonnanius" pageId="5" pageNumber="458" rank="species" species="bonnanius">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="458">H. bonnanius</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is slightly more colorful and it is worthwhile to recapitulate it here. Its original description (
<bibRefCitation author="Jousseaume, F" journalOrPublisher="Bulletin de la Societe Philomathique de Paris" pageId="7" pageNumber="460" pagination="5 - 44" refId="B17" refString="Jousseaume, F, 1900. Mollusques terrestres. Clausilia, Rhodea et Bulimus Sud-Americanae. Bulletin de la Societe Philomathique de Paris 2: 5 - 44" title="Mollusques terrestres. Clausilia, Rhodea et Bulimus Sud-Americanae." volume="2" year="1900">Jousseaume 1900</bibRefCitation>
) was based upon the work of the Jesuit scholar Filippo Buonanni (1638-1723), who compiled the first conchology manual (
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.5962/bhl.title.119125" author="Buonanni, F" journalOrPublisher="Felice Cefaretti, Rome" pageId="7" pageNumber="460" refId="B8" refString="Buonanni, F, 1681. Ricreatione dell'occhio e della mente. Nell'offeruatione delle Chiocciole, proposta a' suriosi delle opere della natura. Felice Cefaretti, Rome" title="Ricreatione dell'occhio e della mente. Nell'offeruatione delle Chiocciole, proposta a' suriosi delle opere della natura." url="https://doi.org/10.5962/bhl.title.119125" year="1681">Buonanni 1681</bibRefCitation>
) and is thus considered the Father of Conchology (
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1163/ej.9789004131880.i-657.52" author="Leonhard, K" editor="Enenkel, KAE" journalOrPublisher="Bulletin de la Societe Philomathique de Paris" pageId="7" pageNumber="460" refId="B18" refString="Leonhard, K, Enenkel, KAE, Smith, MS, 2007. Brill, Leiden. https://doi.org/10.1163/ej.9789004131880.i-657.52" title="Brill, Leiden" url="https://doi.org/10.1163/ej.9789004131880.i-657.52" year="2007">Leonhard 2007</bibRefCitation>
). As 
<bibRefCitation author="Pilsbry, HA" journalOrPublisher="Academy of Natural Sciences of Philadelphia, Philadelphia" pageId="8" pageNumber="461" refId="B29" refString="Pilsbry, HA, 1901. Manual of conchology, second series. Pulmonata. Vol. 14. Oriental bulimoid Helicidae; Odontostomidae; Cerionidae. Academy of Natural Sciences of Philadelphia, Philadelphia" title="Manual of conchology, second series. Pulmonata. Vol. 14. Oriental bulimoid Helicidae; Odontostomidae; Cerionidae." year="1901">Pilsbry (1901)</bibRefCitation>
argued, 
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.5962/bhl.title.119125" author="Buonanni, F" journalOrPublisher="Felice Cefaretti, Rome" pageId="7" pageNumber="460" refId="B8" refString="Buonanni, F, 1681. Ricreatione dell'occhio e della mente. Nell'offeruatione delle Chiocciole, proposta a' suriosi delle opere della natura. Felice Cefaretti, Rome" title="Ricreatione dell'occhio e della mente. Nell'offeruatione delle Chiocciole, proposta a' suriosi delle opere della natura." url="https://doi.org/10.5962/bhl.title.119125" year="1681">
<normalizedToken originalValue="Buonanni’s">Buonanni's</normalizedToken>
(1681)
</bibRefCitation>
description of his Turbine #44 and its illustration (allowing for some distortion in the drawing) are vastly consistent with 
<taxonomicName genus="H." lsidName="H. ramagei" pageId="5" pageNumber="458" rank="species" species="ramagei">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="458">H. ramagei</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Despite later authors such as Linnaeus having relied on 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Buonanni’s">Buonanni's</normalizedToken>
work, this particular species was overlooked until 
<bibRefCitation author="Jousseaume, F" journalOrPublisher="Bulletin de la Societe Philomathique de Paris" pageId="7" pageNumber="460" pagination="5 - 44" refId="B17" refString="Jousseaume, F, 1900. Mollusques terrestres. Clausilia, Rhodea et Bulimus Sud-Americanae. Bulletin de la Societe Philomathique de Paris 2: 5 - 44" title="Mollusques terrestres. Clausilia, Rhodea et Bulimus Sud-Americanae." volume="2" year="1900">Jousseaume (1900)</bibRefCitation>
published it as 
<taxonomicName authority="Jousseaume, 1900" authorityName="Jousseaume" authorityYear="1900" class="Gastropoda" family="Odontostomidae" genus="Bonnanius" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Bonnanius Bonnanius" order="Stylommatophora" pageId="5" pageNumber="458" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="Bonnanius">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="458">Bonnanius Bonnanius</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, misspelling the 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Jesuit’s">Jesuit's</normalizedToken>
name and likely without knowing the work of 
<bibRefCitation author="Smith, EA" journalOrPublisher="Journal of the Linnean Society of London" pageId="8" pageNumber="461" pagination="483 - 503" refId="B39" refString="Smith, EA, 1890. Mollusca. Journal of the Linnean Society of London 20: 483 - 503" title="Mollusca." volume="20" year="1890">Smith (1890)</bibRefCitation>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="6" pageNumber="459">
<pageBreakToken pageId="6" pageNumber="459" start="start">The</pageBreakToken>
shell features of 
<taxonomicName genus="H." lsidName="H. ramagei" pageId="6" pageNumber="459" rank="species" species="ramagei">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="459">H. ramagei</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
display some morphological variation: (1) shell size, from some rather small specimens to very large ones (Hmin = 16 mm and Hmax = 22 mm); (2) shell color can go from entirely brown to marked with four white spiral bands; (3) aperture size, relative to remainder of the shell; (4) shell shape, with some specimens having a much shorter spire (
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="F3" captionText="Figure 3. Hyperaulax ramagei. A-E. Lectotype, NHMUK 1988.6.24.163. F-J. Paralectotypes  1 to  5 (in order), including large forms in apparent sub-fossil state, NHMUK 1988.6.24.164 - 170. K. Specimen without the white spiral bands, NHMUK 1902.10.16.4." figureDoi="10.3897/zse.95.38259.figure3" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/339176" pageId="6" pageNumber="459" tableDoi="10.3897/zse.95.38259.figure3">
Fig. 3
<normalizedToken originalValue="A–C">A-C</normalizedToken>
</figureCitation>
, lectotype); (5) two parietal teeth might be absent (
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="F3" captionText="Figure 3. Hyperaulax ramagei. A-E. Lectotype, NHMUK 1988.6.24.163. F-J. Paralectotypes  1 to  5 (in order), including large forms in apparent sub-fossil state, NHMUK 1988.6.24.164 - 170. K. Specimen without the white spiral bands, NHMUK 1902.10.16.4." figureDoi="10.3897/zse.95.38259.figure3" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/339176" pageId="6" pageNumber="459" tableDoi="10.3897/zse.95.38259.figure3">Fig. 3I</figureCitation>
); (6) the surface of the palatal tooth goes from nearly smooth (
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="F3" captionText="Figure 3. Hyperaulax ramagei. A-E. Lectotype, NHMUK 1988.6.24.163. F-J. Paralectotypes  1 to  5 (in order), including large forms in apparent sub-fossil state, NHMUK 1988.6.24.164 - 170. K. Specimen without the white spiral bands, NHMUK 1902.10.16.4." figureDoi="10.3897/zse.95.38259.figure3" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/339176" pageId="6" pageNumber="459" tableDoi="10.3897/zse.95.38259.figure3">Fig. 3I, J</figureCitation>
) to serrated (
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="F3" captionText="Figure 3. Hyperaulax ramagei. A-E. Lectotype, NHMUK 1988.6.24.163. F-J. Paralectotypes  1 to  5 (in order), including large forms in apparent sub-fossil state, NHMUK 1988.6.24.164 - 170. K. Specimen without the white spiral bands, NHMUK 1902.10.16.4." figureDoi="10.3897/zse.95.38259.figure3" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/339176" pageId="6" pageNumber="459" tableDoi="10.3897/zse.95.38259.figure3">Fig. 3F, G</figureCitation>
), with up to three distinct points (
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="F3" captionText="Figure 3. Hyperaulax ramagei. A-E. Lectotype, NHMUK 1988.6.24.163. F-J. Paralectotypes  1 to  5 (in order), including large forms in apparent sub-fossil state, NHMUK 1988.6.24.164 - 170. K. Specimen without the white spiral bands, NHMUK 1902.10.16.4." figureDoi="10.3897/zse.95.38259.figure3" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/339176" pageId="6" pageNumber="459" tableDoi="10.3897/zse.95.38259.figure3">Fig. 3A</figureCitation>
), reminiscent of the carnassial tooth of 
<taxonomicName genus="Bales" lsidName="Bales" order="Carnivora" pageId="6" pageNumber="459" rank="order">Carnivora</taxonomicName>
(apparently this is not related to the age of the individual or to the freshness of the specimen when collected). The syntype of 
<taxonomicName genus="H." lsidName="H. bouvieri" pageId="6" pageNumber="459" rank="species" species="bouvieri">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="459">H. bouvieri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
show a four-pronged palatal tooth, which is also unusually large, and a three-pronged parietal tooth (
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 4" captionStartId="F4" captionText="Figure 4. Hyperaulax ramagei. A-C. Syntype of Bonnanius bouvieri, MNHN-IM- 2000 - 28020 (MNHN). D. Reproduction of &quot; Turbine  44 &quot; of Buonanni (1861), the holotype of Bonnanius bonnanius. E. Protoconch detail, NHMUK 1902.10.16.4." figureDoi="10.3897/zse.95.38259.figure4" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/339177" pageId="6" pageNumber="459" tableDoi="10.3897/zse.95.38259.figure4">
Fig. 4
<normalizedToken originalValue="A–C">A-C</normalizedToken>
</figureCitation>
); this could be seen as morphological variation, but, as this specimen bears a mark of breakage near the aperture and further growth (
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 4" captionStartId="F4" captionText="Figure 4. Hyperaulax ramagei. A-C. Syntype of Bonnanius bouvieri, MNHN-IM- 2000 - 28020 (MNHN). D. Reproduction of &quot; Turbine  44 &quot; of Buonanni (1861), the holotype of Bonnanius bonnanius. E. Protoconch detail, NHMUK 1902.10.16.4." figureDoi="10.3897/zse.95.38259.figure4" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/339177" pageId="6" pageNumber="459" tableDoi="10.3897/zse.95.38259.figure4">Fig. 4C</figureCitation>
), it could be simply post-trauma anomalous growth. For a comparison with its single congener, 
<taxonomicName genus="H." lsidName="H. ridleyi" pageId="6" pageNumber="459" rank="species" species="ridleyi">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="459">H. ridleyi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, see the Discussion section of that species.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="6" pageNumber="459">
Some of the specimens available (including some paralectotypes) appear to be of a sub-fossil state, as already noted by 
<bibRefCitation author="Smith, EA" journalOrPublisher="Journal of the Linnean Society of London" pageId="8" pageNumber="461" pagination="483 - 503" refId="B39" refString="Smith, EA, 1890. Mollusca. Journal of the Linnean Society of London 20: 483 - 503" title="Mollusca." volume="20" year="1890">Smith (1890)</bibRefCitation>
. These appear to be larger than the fresh specimens, but this could be due to collection bias towards larger specimens; at present, there is not enough sub-fossil material for a statistically meaningful assessment.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
